    "Layout": {}
  },
  "markup": "\u003Cp\u003EFor a long time, writing for search and writing for humans were treated as competing goals. Keyword density pulled one way, clarity pulled the other, and the result was prose that served neither audience particularly well. The good news is that the tension has largely dissolved \u2014 the same qualities that help a page rank today are the ones that help a person read it.\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Ch2\u003EStart with the question, not the keyword\u003C/h2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EEvery useful page answers a question. Before drafting, write the question down in plain language. \u201CHow do I pick a CMS for a small marketing team?\u201D is a better starting point than a keyword list. The keywords will come naturally from the answer; the answer will not come naturally from the keywords.\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Ch2\u003EWrite the summary first\u003C/h2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EA two-sentence summary at the top of the page does double duty: it tells the reader whether they are in the right place, and it gives search engines a clean signal about the page\u2019s purpose. If you cannot write the summary, the page is not ready.\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Ch2\u003EUse headings the way a reader would\u003C/h2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EHeadings are navigation, not decoration. A reader scanning the page should be able to reconstruct the argument from the headings alone. If yours read like \u201CIntroduction, Background, Details, Conclusion,\u201D rewrite them until they carry meaning on their own.\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Ch2\u003ELink with intent\u003C/h2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EInternal links help readers go deeper and help search engines understand the shape of your site. Link to the page that genuinely answers the next question, not to whatever happens to be topically adjacent. \u201CClick here\u201D helps no one; the link text should describe what is on the other side.\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Ch2\u003EThe test that matters\u003C/h2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ERead the piece aloud. If a sentence makes you stumble, it will make a reader stumble too. Search engines have spent years getting better at rewarding writing that respects the reader \u2014 the easiest way to optimise for both audiences is to stop treating them as separate.\u003C/p\u003E"
}]]></Value>
    </bodyText>
